### Register a new user with the JWT-based AuthenticationController (api-version-neutral).
### On success the response carries a Bearer token; the same token is what the JWT
### claims pipeline parses into `Actor.Id = sub` for resource-based authorization on
### every subsequent /hosts, /hosts/{...}/menus, /hosts/{...}/dinners, /reservations,
### and /menu-reviews call.

POST {{host}}/authentication/register
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "userId": "xavierjohn2023",
    "firstName": "Xavier",
    "lastName": "John",
    "email": "someone@somewhere.com",
    "password": "Amiko1232!"
}

### Expected response shape:
### HTTP/1.1 200 OK
### Content-Type: application/json
### {
###   "userId": "xavierjohn2023",
###   "firstName": "Xavier",
###   "lastName": "John",
###   "email": "someone@somewhere.com",
###   "token": "eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..."
### }
###
### Failure modes:
###   - Re-registering the same userId -> 409 / 422 with code `user.already_exists`
###     (per Errors.User.AlreadyExists, surfaced by ValidateUserDoesNotExist in
###     RegisterCommandHandler).
###   - Invalid payload (empty fields, bad email, weak password) -> 422 with a per-field
###     Problem Details body from the Required* primitives' TryCreate validators.
###
### Copy the `token` from the response into `@token = ...` at the top of the other
### .http files (they send it as `Authorization: Bearer {{token}}`).
